n the other hand, he advocated programs of cultural synthesis and political autonomy which were a distinct departure from the paternalist notions of the 1880s and 1890s. His support of such ideas was fostered by the influence of leading anthropologists such as Horatio Hale but also by his own extensive travel and observation of Indians, particularly the Cherokee Indians of Oklahoma. This book describes the efforts of a nineteenth-century Canadian missionary who entertained radical notions of Indian self-government and cultural synthesis, as well as more conventional ideas of native assimilation and cultural replacement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndians of North AmericaxCultural assimilationxCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxCultural assimilationzCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxMissionsxCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxMissionszCanada. 0aMissionariesxBiographyxCanadaxCanada. 0aMissionarieszCanadavBiography. 0aOjibwa IndiansxCultural assimilation. 0aOjibwa IndiansxMissions. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aHistory. 4aReligion. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920664940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889206649423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889206649/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles